armaceutical companies. Skin Theory examines the prison as this space for scientific knowledge production, showing how the “perfect control conditions” of the prison dovetailed into the visual regimes of laboratory work. To that end, Skin Theory offers an important reframing of visual approaches to race in histories of science, medicine, and technology, shifting from issues of scientific racsm to the scientific rationality of racism itself. In this highly original work, Cristina Mejia Visperas approaches science as a fundamentally racial project by analyzing the privileged object and instrument of Kligman’s experiments: the skin. She theorizes the skin as visual technology, as built environment, and as official discourse, developing a compelling framework for understanding the intersections of race, incarceration, and medical science in postwar America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDermatologyxResearchzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aHuman experimentation in medicinezPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPrisonersxHealth and hygienezPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacism in criminal justice administrationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacism in medicinezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh  aAlbert Kligman.  aArmy experiments.  aAssata Shakur.  aFrantz Fanon.  aGeorge Jackson.  aHolmesburg Prison.  aNational Commission for the Protection of Human Subjects of Biomedical and Behavioral Research.  aNuremberg Trials.  aWorld War II.  aagency.  abioethics.  aclinical trials.  adermatology.  aflesh.  aghost.  ahistology.  ainformed consent.  alaboratory.  amedical science.  amonoprint.  apain.  apatch test.  aphotomicrograph.  aposthumanism.  aprison architectu